{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f64ecb86-4888-408f-bdb9-2a5fcf76db1c","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I can't inspect it directly. Here's how to diagnose and configure dumps on **your** machine:\n\n---\n\n### Step 1 — Identify the runtime\n\n```bash\n# If libcoreclr.so appears, it's CoreCLR. If not, it's NativeAOT.\ngrep -q libcoreclr /proc/12345/maps && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"NativeAOT\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Step 2 — Configure crash dumps\n\n**For either runtime**, enable Linux core dumps first:\n\n```bash\n# Allow unlimited core size for the process\nprlimit --pid 12345 --core=unlimited\n\n# Set a dump directory (persistent across crashes)\nsudo mkdir -p /var/crash/dotnet\nsudo sysctl -w kernel.core_pattern=\"/var/crash/dotnet/core.%e.%p.%t\"\n```\n\n**If CoreCLR** — you can also use the built-in `createdump` facility:\n\n```bash\n# These env vars must be set BEFORE the app starts (restart required):\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1          # enable auto-dump on crash\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4            # 4 = full heap dump (1=mini, 2=withheap, 3=triage)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=\"/var/crash/dotnet/coredump.%p.%t\"\n```\n\nCoreCLR's `createdump` produces richer managed metadata than a raw kernel core dump, so prefer this method.\n\n**If NativeAOT** — there is no `createdump`; rely on the kernel `core_pattern` above. The dumps are standard ELF cores — analyze with `gdb` or `lldb`.\n\n---\n\n### Step 3 — Verify\n\n```bash\n# Send SIGABRT to test (⚠️ kills the process!)\n# kill -6 12345\n# Then check:\nls -la /var/crash/dotnet/\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Run the `grep libcoreclr` check first. CoreCLR → use `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`. NativeAOT → use `kernel.core_pattern`. Both benefit from `ulimit -c unlimited`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"db17f431-d106-429c-9ccb-5ef86fb7108e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine. That's expected — PID 12345 is on the user's machine, not here. I should give them the commands to run themselves, and explain the logic for both scenarios.","outputTokens":633,"requestId":"1B85:1007E7:165BB94:1916A6A:6A0287E8"},"id":"cef5fb42-1499-4657-b2db-c093dbe26a33","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:52:56.136Z","parentId":"fb8ddddb-4767-4b72-9c70-ef3c3531df02"}
